column109: OEYC/Family Support Drop-In Programs (drop-in programs for children ages 0-6 and their parents/caregivers. column110: Adult Drop-In (Adult Drop-in offers a safe, welcoming space for homeless and marginally housed individuals offering nutritious meals, showers, hygiene products, harm reduction supplies, pet food and supplies, computer and phone access, social activities and group outings, volunteer and participant engagement opportunities, skill building opportunities, information and referral services, and access to a variety of LAMP services and professionals through our integrated service model.)
column116: SEYA (A youth led, youth run group who work together to make a positive difference in the community. They organize events to showcase youth talents, creativity and ideas (ex. Annual Ruckus Fashion and Talent Showcase). SEYA youth also host workshops on leadership, skills development, teamwork, youth issues and create opportunities for experiential learning (ie learning by "doing"). SEYA's long term vision is to provide ongoing opportunities for advocacy, civic engagement, and volunteer hours. This is to support the health and capacity of the youth here in the Lakeshore.)
column117: Street Level Youth Programs (A free Drop-In Centre for TWEENS (ages 10 to 13) & TEENS (ages 14-19) in South Etobicoke.  Street Level works with youth to make healthy lifestyle choices through life skill development workshops, physical recreational activities, volunteer and leadership opportunities, and a positive social support network.  Snacks and/or meals are served at all programs.  This program facilitates a summer camp program as well.)
column118: ASK! Community Information (Operating since 1969, ASK! Community Information Centre provides a variety of programs and services.  Food is offered on an as-needed basis to the program participants.  ASK! also runs the Infant Emergency Food Bank for families in need.)
column119: Rathburn Area Youth (This youth driven centre focuses on youth empowerment, leadership, the pursuit of education, and equipping youth with the information  and support they need to make healthy life choices.  Light meals and snacks are served at each program.)
column120: Among Friends (The Among Friends Program is a social/recreation program for adults who live with mental health challenges that have significantly affected their quality of life.  Snacks and light meals provided at each program.)

column11: All of our programs at PCHC would suffer greatly if we no longer had the ability to provide food to our clients, either for take home or preparation of shared meals on site. Food is an invitation and a bridge to our programs and services, allowing us to engage with marginalized populations while addressing this important social determinant of health. Food allows us to engage people, on street outreach, through the drop-in, and in all of our programs (e.g. ID clinics, KAPOW women's weekly drop-in, Seniors groups, childminding classes, etc.). Our programs would be much less effective without food and, most certainly, attendance would decrease. Without doubt, engagement made possible through Second Harvest food has prevented an HIV infection, decreased the social isolation of a senior, educated sex workers about self-care, connected an uninsured newcomer with primary care, brought a mother into prenatal careÉliterally, without exaggeration, it saves lives.

column11: the seniors we serve have very limited incomes.  We service a very financially marginalised demographic who can not afford to buy much food. By receiving Second Harvest food rescue donations we are able to ensure that the most vulnerable seniors in our community receive  wholesome fresh fruits and vegetables and non perishables items. Without the food from Second Harvest our seniors would have very limited access to fresh and healthy foods and would be forced to eat mainly processed and unhealthy foods that mainly consist of carbohydrates. Our programs would also suffer - we offer weekly cooking and baking classes and use many food items from Second Harvest as our ingredients. Our snack pass would also suffer as we use many of the donations during programs to offer our seniors healthy and nutritious snacks at the end of each program Without the donations of second harvest we would not be able to offer these great programs.

column11: Without the food from Second Harvest, our organization would be unable to offer fresh fruits and vegetables, or any other healthy food, to the refugee claimants who live at Romero House and who come from the broader community to receive Second Harvest food here. Refugees would have to cut into an already very-limited pool of financial resources to purchase food and, typically, would not have the financial means to afford to purchase healthy food from the grocery store. They may purchase processed foods instead, or not have the capacity to purchase much food at all. Considering that many families who are supported by Romero House have children (sometimes even 4-5 children in their family), it is easy to imagine how expensive food would be for this family to purchase! Second Harvest ensures that individuals and families with children are well-fed and able to begin adjusting to life here in Canada.

column6: Food security: Second Harvest donations provide reliable access to nutritious food and increase the overall amount that clients can purchase in a month, contributing to participants' physical and mental health.
column7: Accessibility: Once registered in our programs, clients do not have to submit documentation, travel, and/or pay any more in transit fare to access food than they otherwise would. Furthermore, clients feel safe in the environment based on their relationships with one another, with staff, and with the space. Despite our efforts, stigma is nonetheless a barrier for some of our clients and our distribution system eliminates much of that.
column8: Advocacy: Second Harvest has helped to start conversations about the cost of living, food (in)security, community resources--or the lack thereof, health, and food waste, among other issues. In addition, participants develop valuable teamwork skills and confidence when they assist with distribution.
column9: Yes, permission to share our response in Second Harvest promotional materials.
column11: Every participant would feel the loss of Second Harvest donations because they help to ease the burden on marginalized clients in language training, skills development, stress management, and employment programming. We serve a range of populations with multiple barriers to access, including immigrant women, sole-support parents, street-involved youth, and OW/ODSP recipients. For some participants, the burden would be particularly heavy without the Second Harvest donations and women are often the first to sacrifice their comfort (including food) for their families' due both to cultural expectations as well as self-imposed pressure.  Recently, a participant disclosed that she is reluctant to visit food banks due not simply to the stigma, but to negative experiences with other service users and the anxiety that it caused. In the absence of Second Harvest, she would either have to access the food bank or more likely, she would have less food to eat.  If participants came to English classes or skills development training hungry or even "simply" worried about their next meal, they would likely find it difficult to focus in class and retain the information they need to overcome language barriers. Absenteeism would likely increase as well due to the fatigue, illness, and anxiety that hunger and stress can create. As a result, participants' performance would suffer as well as their relationships with their peers and the agency as a whole.   Furthermore, participants would lose organic opportunities to discuss food (in)security, hunger, and the cost of living with people in different programs and they might hesitate to approach settlement staff to enquire about food banks, despite our best efforts to raise awareness about these services.

column280: This year, Newcomer Women's Services Toronto (NEW) introduced Cook It! - Stress Management & Self Care for Single Mothers and Employment Ontario's Youth Job Connection. Between the two programs, an additional 170 persons accessed NEW.   Cook It! included single mothers in receipt of Ontario Works (OW) and their children. Given that clients had limited financial resources, they often had limited access to fresh, nutritious food and cooking itself became a fraught process as they tried to meet their own and their children's needs in a busy household. The program aimed not only to bring women together through food, but to bring the joy back to cooking and provide participants with enough food to take home. While the program included a budget for food, Second Harvest helped to supplement the menu and gave women a little more to take home with them if they wanted to recycle the recipe.  Employment Ontario's Youth Job Connection (YJC) provides pre-employment training and job placement to unemployed or under-employed youth with multiple barriers to labour market access. YJC clientele include racialized, homeless or street-involved, and immigrant youth; youth with mental health concerns, addiction issues, and/or disabilities; and others. Youth Outreach Workers provide youth with snacks during training to help them maintain their focus and recognizing that many youth have limited financial means, staff routinely send participants home with nutritious food items to help them.  Clients in the mainstream Employment Ontario program (some of whom receive Ontario Works and/or face barriers to labour market access) have benefited from Second Harvest donations as well after they disclosed that they were struggling financially.

The food bank would provide significantly less food items to clients on a weekly basis without the support from Second Harvest. Often we are able to stretch key items like dairy and produce because we have more options with the products we receive.  Our Family Resource Centre would have to either eliminate providing healthy snacks or significantly cut back on the quantities we provide. This may mean prioritizing which programs we can serve snacks at while cutting others all together.

column6: Second Harvest organizes and delivers up to 70 lunches for children attending our Summer Camp each day of the Summer Camp.These lunches are: nutritious, healthy and varied in their content. The lunches support a program which sees 25% of the children starting their day with no breakfast. Without these healthy lunches, children would bring a lunch which in many cases would be barely minimal. The Second Harvest lunches hugely support children in our community.
column7: The out of the cold program depends on Second Harvest donations for snacks that we provide, twice a day. The snacks provided are regularly from Second Harvest donations and are necessary for the residents who arrive at 5:30 pm, as many may not have anything to eat all day, we provide something for them to eat before dinner is served later.
column8: Second Harvest donations are used to supplement a portion of our bagged lunches so that we could provide a nutritious yet delicious bagged lunch for those who are not residents of the shelter. We want our bagged lunches to be just as delicious and filling as our dinner to ensure the the people who are dropping by to get bagged lunch are being fed wholesome food.
column9: Yes, permission to share our response in Second Harvest promotional materials.
column11: For OOTC: We cannot imagine not having food from Second Harvest as the majority of our snacks that we provide twice a day for the participants in the "Out of the Cold" program are regularly from these donations. We also use Second Harvest donations to supplement some of our foods for every dinner that we provide. Without Second Harvest, we would not be able to feed 85 participants on the weekend as we would have a shortage and lack of food. We also use the donations to package bagged lunches for people who are not staying at the shelter, therefore, we would no longer be able to provide a more nutritious meal for them outside of a generic PBJ sandwich. For summer camp: from the nutrition value, to the variety of lunches, to the timing - we depend so much on the lunches for Summer Camp! And the parents appreciate so much that their children have a healthy lunch as part of the their daily routine.

column109: Out of the Cold: We offer emergency based shelter on Friday, Saturday and Sunday nights to those who find themselves in need. We serve 1200 unique participants annually, who are served with Second Harvest food. We offer shlter as well as snacks, dinner and breakfast. Beds are on a first come, first served basis. Available services include meals, accommodations, a clothing bank, shower facilities during program hours, a social worker to provide counseling and referrals to other services including medical and housing. We are open from 5:30 pm to 7 am, Friday-Sunday from October to May and Saturday and Sunday only from June to September.
column110: Summer Camp: We offer a day camp for the summer months for ages 4 to 13. Camps are dividied into age groupiong (4-5, 6-7, 8-13 and there is also an Academic camp. Each week we have approximately 70 children a day registered for the the summer camp, 120 unique children each year.
